<TITLE> Rescuers fail to reach 18 trapped miners in China </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Dec 19,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - More than a day after 18 miners were trapped by a coal mine blast, rescuers still could not enter the mine in central China's Hunan Province because of high levels of gas, Xinhua quoted officials as saying late on Thursday. "Chances of their survival were slim," said Shi Jinchu, vice director of the Lianyuan city's production safety bureau. More than 800 tons of coal blocked a 120-meter section of the mine seam, hampering rescue work, said the report. China's mining industry is the world's most dangerous. A total of 3,786 coal miners died in gas blasts, floodings and other accidents last year as companies, often flouting safety regulations, rushed to feed demand from a booming economy. This year, coal mine accidents claimed 2,690 lives in the first 10 months, a drop of 13.5 percent as thousands of small, unsafe mines across the country were closed
